{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17520019","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17520019"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:19:02+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:19:02+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13131"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13131","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13131"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.25,0.53,0.05,0.15]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5568"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"82836"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5568","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5568"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13131"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67939"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"2089"},{"type":"tags","id":"5851"},{"type":"tags","id":"5931"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"9462"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9757"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10584"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"82836","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/82836"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 57-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a 30-minute episode of vertigo that was associated with aural fullness and tinnitus during the attack. This is the fifth such episode she has had in the last six months. On previous occasions, her symptoms resolved spontaneously and she did not seek medical attention. She has a five pack-year smoking history, drinks a glass of wine daily and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Her external and middle ears appear normal, with mobile tympanic membranes and no fluid in the middle ear space. The strength of her facial muscles is normal bilaterally in all branches of the facial nerve (graded as 5/5). The Weber test and Rinne test are unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate plan of management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Intratympanic gentamicin injections","Prochlorperazine maleate","Lifestyle modifications","Labyrinthectomy","Thiazide diuretics"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe patient\u0027s symptoms and examination findings are suggestive of Meniere\u0027s disease, a disorder of the inner ear characterised by recurrent episodic vertigo lasting at least 20 minutes, often associated with aural fullness, tinnitus and hearing loss during attacks. \u003Cstrong\u003ELifestyle modifications\u003C/strong\u003E are the appropriate first-line management and should be trialled before considering medical or surgical interventions. This involves avoiding triggers (such as chocolate, caffeine and tobacco), restricting sodium intake, maintaining adequate fluid intake, practicing stress management, engaging in regular exercise, and ensuring consistent sleep patterns.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThiazide diuretics\u003C/strong\u003E may help reduce the frequency and severity of vertigo attacks by reducing fluid buildup in the inner ear. However, these should only be considered if lifestyle modifications alone prove insufficient in managing symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProchlorperazine maleate\u003C/strong\u003E can help relieve acute vertigo symptoms but does not address the underlying cause or prevent future episodes. It should be reserved for symptomatic relief during acute attacks rather than as first-line management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntratympanic gentamicin injections\u003C/strong\u003E are used in cases of severe Meniere\u0027s disease that are unresponsive to conservative management. This treatment carries a risk of hearing loss and should only be considered after failure of less invasive options.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELabyrinthectomy\u003C/strong\u003E is a last resort surgical option for patients with severe, debilitating Meniere\u0027s disease that has failed to respond to all other treatments. It results in complete loss of hearing in the affected ear and should never be considered as initial management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETreatment for Meniere\u0027s disease follows a stepwise approach, starting with conservative measures and progressing to more invasive options only if symptoms remain poorly controlled. The goal is to achieve symptom control with the least invasive intervention possible.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Lifestyle modifications including sodium restriction, stress management, and trigger avoidance are first-line treatment for Meniere\u0027s disease.","Medical and surgical interventions should only be considered after lifestyle modifications have failed.","The severity and frequency of symptoms guide the stepwise progression of treatment from conservative to invasive options."],"references":["Hoskin JL. Meniere\u2019s disease: new guidelines, subtypes, imaging, and more. Curr Opin Neurol. 2022; 35:90-97.","Harcourt J, Barraclough K, Bronstein AM. Meniere\u0027s disease. BMJ. 2014 Nov 12;349: g6544."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67939"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13131"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67939","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/67939"},"attributes"